>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>WiFi vs. Ethernet for Gaming</h1>
      <p>The definitive latency comparison. Stop relying on invisible waves for your competitive matchmaking.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Interactive Tool -->
    <div class="card tool-container">
      <div class="quiz-header">
        <h2>Network Upgrade Finder</h2>
        <p>Can't run a 50-foot Ethernet cable across your living room? Take this quick diagnostic to find the best low-latency alternative for your specific home setup.</p>
      </div>

      <div id="quiz-container">
        <div id="q1" class="quiz-question active">
          <h3>1. Do you have coaxial (cable TV) ports in the room with your router AND the room with your gaming PC/Console?</h3>
          <button class="quiz-btn" onclick="nextQuestion('q1', 'result-moca')">Yes, in both rooms</button>
          <button class="quiz-btn" onclick="nextQuestion('q1', 'q2')">No, missing one or both</button>
        </div>

        <div id="q2" class="quiz-question" style="display: none;">
          <h3>2. Was your house/apartment built or fully rewired recently (in the last 15-20 years)?</h3>
          <button class="quiz-btn" onclick="nextQuestion('q2', 'result-powerline')">Yes, modern wiring</button>
          <button class="quiz-btn" onclick="nextQuestion('q2', 'q3')">No, it's an older building</button>
        </div>

        <div id="q3" class="quiz-question" style="display: none;">
          <h3>3. Is your gaming device close enough to the router that there are only 1 or 2 normal walls (no brick/concrete) between them?</h3>
          <button class="quiz-btn" onclick="nextQuestion('q3', 'result-mesh')">Yes, fairly close</button>
          <button class="quiz-btn" onclick="nextQuestion('q3', 'result-drilling')">No, it's far / thick walls</button>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Quiz Results -->
      <div id="result-moca" class="quiz-result" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Your Best Option: <span class="highlight-text">MoCA Adapters</span></h3>
        <p><strong>Multimedia over Coax Alliance (MoCA)</strong> is your golden ticket. Since your house is already wired for cable TV, you can buy a pair of MoCA adapters. One plugs into your router and a coax port, the other plugs into your PC and the coax port in your room. It converts the coaxial line into an incredibly fast, ultra-low-latency Ethernet line. It is almost identical in performance to running a dedicated Cat6 cable.</p>
        <button class="secondary-btn" onclick="resetQuiz()">Retake Quiz</button>
      </div>

      <div id="result-powerline" class="quiz-result" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Your Best Option: <span class="highlight-text">Powerline Adapters</span></h3>
        <p>Since you have modern electrical wiring, a <strong>Powerline Ethernet Adapter</strong> is your best bet. You plug one adapter into the wall near your router, and the other near your PC. They transmit the internet signal through your home's copper electrical wires. While the total download speed might be slower than high-end WiFi, the latency is much more stable, eliminating the jitter that ruins gaming.</p>
        <button class="secondary-btn" onclick="resetQuiz()">Retake Quiz</button>
      </div>

      <div id="result-mesh" class="quiz-result" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Your Best Option: <span class="highlight-text">A Tri-Band WiFi 6/6E Router</span></h3>
        <p>Since your walls aren't too thick, but you can't use MoCA or Powerline, you are forced to use WiFi. To game properly on WiFi, you need a high-end <strong>Tri-Band WiFi 6E Router</strong>. Ensure your gaming PC/Console connects <em>exclusively</em> to the 5GHz or 6GHz band. Never game on the 2.4GHz band. Read our <a href="/router-settings-guide">Router Settings Guide</a> to ensure your channels are optimized.</p>
        <button class="secondary-btn" onclick="resetQuiz()">Retake Quiz</button>
      </div>

      <div id="result-drilling" class="quiz-result" style="display: none;">
        <h3>Your Best Option: <span class="highlight-text">Bite the Bullet & Run a Cable</span></h3>
        <p>You have old electrical wiring, no coax ports, and thick walls or a long distance to the router. You have exhausted all workarounds. You need to buy a long <strong>Cat6 flat Ethernet cable</strong>. You can run flat cables under baseboards, under the edges of carpets, or along the ceiling using adhesive clips. It's the only way you will get a playable connection for competitive games.</p>
        <button class="secondary-btn" onclick="resetQuiz()">Retake Quiz</button>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Article Content -->
    <div class="article-content">
      <p>Before proceeding, ensure you understand the difference between Bandwidth and Latency. If you don't, check our <a href="/network-optimization-guide">Ultimate Network Optimization Guide</a>.</p>

      <h2>The Physics of the Problem</h2>
      <p>Every year, router manufacturers slap aggressive red accents and spider-like antennas onto a plastic box and market it as a "Gaming Router." They boast about "Gigabit Wireless Speeds" and "WiFi 6E Technology."</p>

      <p>Here is the hard truth: <strong>For real-time, competitive online gaming, a $5 Ethernet cable from a hardware store will outperform a $400 "Gaming" WiFi Router every single time.</strong></p>

      <p>The problem is physics. WiFi relies on radio waves broadcasting through the air. These waves are subject to interference from walls, furniture, your neighbor's router, Bluetooth headphones, and even your microwave. Ethernet sends electrical signals through a shielded, dedicated copper wire directly to your machine.</p>

      <h2>The Three Pillars of Network Performance</h2>

      <h3>1. Packet Loss (The Silent Killer)</h3>
      <p>In gaming, your computer is constantly sending small packets of data (e.g., "I moved left", "I pulled the trigger") to the server. On a wired Ethernet connection, packet loss is virtually 0%. Every command arrives.</p>
      <p>On WiFi, interference can cause a packet to simply vanish into the air. When the server realizes it missed a packet, it has to ask your PC to send it again. This results in the game freezing for a split second, "rubber-banding" (teleporting backward), or your shots simply not registering. <strong>Ethernet eliminates this entirely.</strong></p>

      <h3>2. Jitter (Ping Stability)</h3>
      <p>Having a low ping is great. Having a <em>stable</em> ping is mandatory.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Ethernet:</strong> Your ping to a server might be a rock-solid 30ms. It stays at exactly 30ms the entire game. Muscle memory kicks in, and you play consistently.</li>
        <li><strong>WiFi:</strong> Your ping might average 32ms. But every few seconds, due to signal processing, it jumps to 45ms, then 80ms, then back to 32ms. This fluctuation is called Jitter. Jitter makes the game feel unresponsive and "floaty."</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>3. Half-Duplex vs. Full-Duplex</h3>
      <p>This is the fundamental technological difference between the two mediums.</p>
      <p><strong>WiFi is Half-Duplex.</strong> This means a WiFi antenna can either send data OR receive data at any given millisecond. It cannot do both simultaneously. Furthermore, if you have 4 devices connected to WiFi, they must all take turns "speaking" to the router. This queueing adds micro-latency to every action.</p>
      <p><strong>Ethernet is Full-Duplex.</strong> An Ethernet cable has dedicated wires for sending data and dedicated wires for receiving data. Your PC can upload your movement data while simultaneously downloading enemy locations, with absolutely zero queueing or wait time.</p>

      <h2>What about WiFi 6 and 6E?</h2>
      <p>WiFi 6 (802.11ax) introduced technologies like OFDMA, which allows the router to communicate with multiple devices simultaneously in a much smarter way than older WiFi 5. WiFi 6E opened up a massive new 6GHz frequency band, essentially adding a private, empty highway for your data, free from your neighbor's 5GHz interference.</p>

      <p>If you absolutely must use WiFi, a modern WiFi 6E router on the 6GHz band is surprisingly good. For casual games, MMOs, and strategy games, it is nearly indistinguishable from Ethernet. However, for hardcore competitive shooters (CS2, Valorant) or fighting games where a 1-frame delay dictates a win or loss, the half-duplex nature of WiFi still leaves you at a slight disadvantage.</p>

      <h2>Network Cable Types Explained</h2>
      <p>If you are finally convinced to run a wire, don't overpay for "gaming" cables. You just need a standard unshielded twisted pair (UTP) cable. Look at the printing on the side of the cable:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Cat5e:</strong> The old standard. Supports speeds up to 1 Gigabit (1000 Mbps). Perfectly fine for almost all gaming scenarios today.</li>
        <li><strong>Cat6:</strong> The current sweet spot. Supports up to 10 Gigabit speeds over short distances and features better internal shielding against crosstalk. If buying new, buy Cat6.</li>
        <li><strong>Cat7 / Cat8:</strong> Expensive overkill. Used for data centers. Do not waste your money on these for a home gaming setup.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>Once you are hardwired, you need to ensure your router is properly managing the traffic. Read our <a href="/router-settings-guide">Optimal Router Settings Guide</a> to configure QoS and eliminate bufferbloat.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    function nextQuestion(currentId, nextId) {
      document.getElementById(currentId).style.display = 'none';
      document.getElementById(nextId).style.display = 'block';
    }

    function resetQuiz() {
      // Hide all results and questions
      document.querySelectorAll('.quiz-question, .quiz-result').forEach(el => {
        el.style.display = 'none';
      });
      // Show first question
      document.getElementById('q1').style.display = 'block';
    }
  </script>

